FBIS3-28104 "dreas023_a_94011" FBIS-EAS-94-023 Document Type:Daily Report 3 February 1994 NORTHEAST ASIA Japan Controversy Over Tax Reform Proposal Reported Hosokawa Announces Tax Cuts OW0202162494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1612 GMT 2 Feb 94 OW0202162494 Tokyo KYODO Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 3 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Thursday [3 February] announced a 6 trillion yen tax reduction plan that includes 5.3 trillion yen in income and resident tax cuts. Hosokawa, announcing the decision at a hastily arranged news conference, said the coalition government will propose abolishing the 3 percent consumption tax but will instead call for imposing a 7 percent national welfare tax. The prime minister said the government plans to make the tax cuts retroactive to January 1, 1994, and to impose the new national welfare tax April 1, 1997. Hosokawa said he has gained agreement at a meeting of top officials of the government and ruling parties.
